editor = "Hodges, Matthew R",
abstract = "Epilepsy is one of the most common neurological diseases in the world; however, a significant number of individuals suffer from uncontrollable epilepsy, placing them at higher risk for post-ictal cardiorespiratory failure and Sudden Unexpected Death in Epilepsy (SUDEP). A landmark study (MORTEMUS) revealed commonalities in the sequence of events leading to SUDEP in patients, which begins with a generalized tonic-clonic seizure (GTCS) followed by respiratory rate suppression, heart rate suppression, and then then respiratory followed by cardiac arrest. Data from our lab using a novel audiogenic seizure rat model (SSkcnj16-/- rats) showed that GTCSs leads to acute respiratory and heart rate suppression which is exacerbated after repeated GTCSs. However, knowledge gaps remain in understanding how repeated seizures lead to this progressive cardiorespiratory dysfunction. Emerging evidence has shown a strong association between neuroinflammation, seizures and epilepsy. Eliciting seizures in different rodent models of epilepsy has led to recruitment of various inflammatory mediators and activation of microglia and astrocytes. This starts a cascade of events leading to the release of cytokines, chemokines and proteases that can damage the surrounding neuronal architecture and even damage the blood brain barrier (BBB) to recruit peripheral immune cells. Clinical studies have shown that severe GTCSs lead to increased levels of cytokines and chemokines in patient serum and samples. Importantly, researchers and clinicians alike are investigating utilizing different anti-inflammatory drugs to help patients with epilepsy reduce the severity and frequency of seizures. Data from human patients who have succumbed to SUDEP show that chemokine receptors and their ligands, such as CCR2/CCL2 and CXCR5/CXCL13, are upregulated in microglia, astrocytes, and neurons in hippocampal, cortical, and cerebellar regions. Therefore, the overarching goal of this project was to understand if repeated seizures lead to neuroinflammation in critical regions of the brainstem important for cardiorespiratory control, and within these regions which cell types play a role, and finally if blocking inflammation may prevent the cardiorespiratory suppression and mortality in our rat model of repeated seizure.Here, I focused on 4 brainstem nuclei critical for cardiorespiratory control: the pre-B{\"o}tzinger complex (preB{\"o}tC; critical for respiratory rhythm generation), the nucleus ambiguous (NA; autonomic and respiratory functions), the B{\"o}tzinger complex (B{\"o}tC; inhibition of inspiration, active expiration), and the medullary raphe nuclei which contains serotonergic (5-HT) neurons that provide critical excitatory drive to breathe and chemoreceptor function. The lab has previously shown that repeated seizures over 10 days led to exacerbation of respiratory rate suppression. In addition, repeated seizure led to increases in Iba-1 (marker for activated microglia) and GFAP (astrocyte/gliosis marker). Preliminary single nuclear RNA sequencing (snRNAseq) within the medullary raphe indicated the recruitment of inflammation in glia and IL1 signaling activation resulting from repeated seizures. These and other data supported the rationale for my work focusing on key brainstem regions involved in cardiorespiratory control and how seizures potentially lead to inflammation. My initial aim focused on determining if inflammation was present after seizure induction(s) within the brainstem cardiorespiratory control network. To investigate this, animals were exposed no seizures (na{\"\i}ve) or to one seizure/day (d) for 3, 7, or 10 d and NA/preB{\"o}tC was isolated for snRNAseq. Importantly, although it has been shown that this brainstem region contains key neuronal populations that are necessary to generate breathing rhythms, the complete cellular composition of this site is not known. Using this approach, I demonstrated that not only were there several subtypes of neurons present in this region, but also that there are subtle but potentially important differences in cellular expression patterns between male and female rats. Furthermore, this study showed that repeated seizures differentially effect microglia and astrocytes in terms of the induction of specific inflammatory pathways, suggesting their activation could result in either a ``pro-inflammatory'' or ``anti-inflammatory'' phenotype. To further clarify which specific cytokines/chemokines may be changing after repeated seizures in this region, I next collected tissues from this region and others in the brainstem and measured inflammatory molecules using a cytokine array for comparison across the na{\"\i}ve state to 1, 2, 3, 5, and 10 d of repeated seizures. The NA/preB{\"o}tC showed the greatest number of significant changes in cytokines, where multiple cytokines were increased especially at 5 d with few changes in cytokines were observed in other brainstem regions across time. This suggested a time- and site-dependent effect of repeated seizures to uniquely increase inflammation within this important brainstem site. My second aim focuses on preventing the adverse effects of repeated seizures in our model by utilizing different classes of anti-inflammatory drugs. Among several cytokines and other inflammation-related molecules we noted that repeated seizures increased IL-1{\ss} and IL-1$\alpha$. Therefore, we sought to broadly inhibit inflammation using a non-steroidal anti-inflammatory (NSAID; ketoprofen), and a specific antagonist to IL-1 receptors, anakinra, to asses if administration of these drugs could improve ventilatory outcomes and prevent seizure-induced mortality across a 10 d seizure protocol. Interestingly, anakinra and ketoprofen were able to prevent some of the respiratory suppression in the immediate post-ictal period (within 15 min), with anakinra having what appeared to be the most beneficial effects by blocking the progressively enhanced respiratory rate suppression across the 10d of seizure. However, animals treated with ketoprofen showed effects like vehicle-treated rats where respiratory rate suppression increased by 4-6 d and had worsened further by 7-10 d than those treated with anakinra. Although anakinra prevented the progressive effect, it was not able to increase survival across the 10d period (not different than vehicle). However, ketoprofen prevented seizure-related mortality despite the lack of effects during the acute post-ictal period. These results suggest that the different pathways may have differential import in this ventilatory system, meaning that IL-1 signaling may be important in acute breathing control post-ictally, but cyclooxygenase (COX) signaling may play a stronger role in preventing mortality with chronic treatment.Overall, these results suggest that repeated seizures induce neuroinflammation in key regions of cardiorespiratory control in a time-and site-dependent manner which involved multiple cell types and signaling pathways. The gene expression profiling data suggests that astrocytes are contributing to the inflammatory pathways recruited after repeated seizures, consistent with previous studies. Moreover, the drug studies herein indicate that blocking the progressive worsening of acute respiratory suppression in the immediate post-ictal period is not sufficient to increase survival after repeated seizures, and that seizure-induced inflammation mediated through COX signaling may have a greater role in seizure-induced mortality in our model. This work provides a deeper understanding of how repeated seizures may drive neuroinflammation in a critical region of the brainstem and highlights a disconnect between respiratory control dysfunction in the immediate post-ictal period and seizure-related mortality.",
